<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[189,1399,1066,1164]" lastBlockId="2.[189,1399,267,399]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
A total of 
<specimenCount box="[304,462,1066,1093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="generic">50 specimens</specimenCount>
were found at five stations. The specimens are placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boeck" authorityYear="1871" box="[1240,1357,1067,1093]" class="Malacostraca" family="Calliopiidae" genus="Halirages" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1240,1357,1067,1093]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Halirages</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the following reasons: labrum rounded apically and acute dorsally, labium with small inner lobes, length of mandible palp article 3 about half that of article 2. Coxal plates small, coxa 1 not expanded distally. Gnathopods 1 and 2 subequal, propodi subrectangular, ischium of pereopod 7 with a small posterodistal process, second epimeral plate with small tooth on posteroventral corner, third epimeral plate smooth. Pereonite 7 with bilobed posterior margin. The uropods of all examined specimens were badly damaged, and only peduncles and proximal parts of rami were available for study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
